Random sampling models

Introduccion

The following article presents a series of fitted models for a random sampling scenario. Two types of models will be established:

  • Models without zeros: in this first scenario the response variable will be transformed in order to present no zero. Also, two types of response variables will be used:

    • Catches: quantitative and continuous variable, it reflects the weight in tons (biomass) of the target species that has been caught.

    • CPUE: quantitative and continuous variable, reflects the catches per unit of effort, the \(CPUE = \frac{Catches}{effort}\), where the effort represents the time that the fishing gear is active (trawling minutes).

    On the other hand, the explanatory variables included in the models will be bathymetry (seabed depth (m)) and effort (time (min) the fishing gear is active), the latter variable will be included in three different ways:

    • As a covariate in the linear predictor

    • As an offset

    • Dividing to catches (CPUE)

  • Models with zeros: once the models have been adjusted with the response variable transformed, we proceeded to the adjustment of hurdle models or delta models. For these models, the response variables and the explanatory variables will follow the same scheme as above.

Model without 0

In this first section, the response variable catches will be transformed in order to eliminate the zeros and obtain the catches per unit of effort (CPUE). Therefore, 0.1 will be added to each of the observation in the study.

# Transform response variable
### Catches
dataset1$abut <- dataset1$abu + 0.1 # add 0.1 to eacho observation
### CPUE
dataset1$CPUE <- dataset1$abu/dataset1$eff
dataset1$CPUEt <- dataset1$abut/dataset1$eff

Descriptive of the response variable

Figure 1 shows the density curve for each of the variables involved in the study, as well as the relationship between them (smoothing and correlation index). It is possible to observe how the response variables catches and CPUE, despite being transformed, have a very heavy tail on the left with a large number of small values. On the other hand, for both response variables the relationship with bathymetry does not seem to be lineal, reaching the maximum of catches/CPUE at intermediate bathymetries.

Result models

All the models have been presented in a complementary document (ANEXO). In order to summarize the information, the following table is presented and the best fitting model is chosen (Table 1).

In line with Table 1, the best model proposed would be number 15, since it has a low DIC and LCPO, 515.15 and 0.5 respectively. However, it has to be checked if the model has a good residual behavior. The formulation of model 15 is as follows:

\[\text{CPUE}(s_{i}) \sim \text{lgnormal} (\mu(s_{i}), \sigma_{i}) \\ \mu(s_{i}) = \beta_{0} + f(B(s_{i})) + u(s_{i}) \\ u(s_{i}) \sim GMRF(0, \Sigma)\]

Model validation

In Figure 2, it can be seen that the residuals oscillate between quite high values, which already indicates problems in the model. Likewise, the fitted values versus the residuals and the observed values also present problem of trend and fit. Consequently, it does not seem that a good fit is being obtained.

Output fixed

In this case, model 15 has only the intercept (\(\beta_{0}\)) as a fixed parameter. The numerical description shows that the mean of the posterior distribution is between -1.86, the standar deviation is 0.15, and the credible interval is -1.86 and -1.60. All this information is also reflected in Figure 3.

On the other hand, it is also interesting to obtain the hyperparameters related to the spatial term. To estimate the Matrn covariance of the spatial term it is necessary to estimate the Matrn correlation (Figure 5) and the variance of the spatial term.

The Matrn correlation function has an unknown parameter k that is indirectly linked to the distance at which the correlation diminishes. The k of the Matern correlation function and the range r of a variogram are brother and sister. In this case, \(k\) has a large value of 26.61, likewise, the mean value of the posterior distribution of sigma is 0.56.

Finally, a heat map (Figure 6) with the distribution of the spatial term is presented. it highlights how the zones with high values of the response variable present a high value in the spatial term.

Output smoothing

For smoothing, a window division of 30 and rw1 (random walk model of order 1) model were used. In Figure 7 it is possible to observe how at low and high bathymetries the values of catchability are low, reaching the maximum of the variable at intermediate bathymetries.

Discussion

In summary, none of the models seems to represent a good fit, this may be because the response variable has been transformed to avoid zeros. Instead of this methodology we should model the zeros. Therefore, in the next section we apply hurdle or delta models.

Models with zeros: Hurdle models

The dataset used on a random sampling, simulating an oceanographic campaign, presents more than 30 % of zeros. For this type of situation it is convenient to use a hurdle model. A hurdle model for continuous data consists of a binary part and a continuous part. The distribution for the binary part will again be the Bernoulli distribution, but for the continuous part we could use a gamma or lgnormal distribution. An extended explanation of the models can be found in the supplemental material.

Result models

Table 2 presents the hurdle models used that have been proposed in the study. In this case, model 1 has been the most satisfactory in terms of DIC and LCPO. The formulation of the model is as follows:

\[\text{Y}(s_{i}) \sim \text{Ber}(\pi(s_{i})) \\ \text{Z}(s_{i}) \sim \text{Gamma}(\mu(s_{i}), \phi) \\ logit(\pi(s_{i})) = \beta_{0Y} + f(B(s_{i})) + u(s_{iY}) \\ u(s_{iY}) \sim \text{GMRF}(0, \Sigma) \\ log(\mu(s_{i})) = \beta_{0Z} + f(B(s_{i})) + u_(s_{iZ}) \\ u(s_{iZ}) \sim \text{GMRF}(0, \Sigma)\]

Model validation

Figure 8 shows a series of graphs that allow us to evaluate whether the model fit is good or not. The graphs show a great improvement compared to the fit of model 15, however, it appears that there aree still some trend problemas.

Output fixed

As in the model of the previous section, there is only one fixed parameter, the intercept. In this case, the confidence interval contains zero so the intercept may be zero. In fact, the probability that the intercept would be zero is 85.71 %.

Discussion

As a conclusion to the adjustment of the hurdle models, the result obtained has been much better than with the initial models, however, it seems that there are still unadjusted trends, so we could try to improve the model (adding more variables, etc.)

Conclusions

Finally, we proceed to list a series of conclusions obtained through the work carried out:

  • The transformed response variable has a very heavy left tail, which implies that there are a large number of small values and this has affected the fitting of the model.

  • The relationship between the response variable and bathymetry is not linear.

  • The response variable could be fitted with a gamma or a lognormal distribution. In this case, the lognormal distribution has given better results in the fit.

  • The model with the best fit quality indicator (DIC and LCPO) is the model 15, which uses the lognormal distribution, an rw1 model for bathymetry, a spatial random effect and CPUE as the response variable.

  • The validation of the model for the response variable without zeros has not been satisfactory, so the results are not reliable.

  • Of the six hurdle models the one with the best fit was model 1: the family used is gamma, the response variable is CPUE, the bathymetry is modeled with a smoothing (rw1) and the spatial term is different for each of the processes (Bernouilli and Gamma).

  • The validation of the best-fit hurdle model shows a substantial improvement compared to the model using the transformed variable. However, there are still problems in the fit.

  • The probability that the hurdle model intercept is 0 is more than 80 %.

  • The spatial field for the two modeled processes are so different.

  • The bathymetry smoothing shows the highest CPUE values at bathymetries between 350-450 meters.

  • It has been demonstrated that it is better to fit hurdle models for variables with large number of zeros.
